data.title: It’s over Luna! I have the high ground!
Don't normally post this kinda stuff.  But wanted to share my new adoption.  Brought him home Thursday night and his name is Sora. He was born April 22nd, and comes from a local animal rescue.

images.description:
Sora was still trying to find a comfy place to lie.  Mouse cord would bug him and he would get up and move.

So Sora came from a local rescue, I'm not sure if he was born at the rescue, or brought to the rescue after birth, the volunteer who did his adoption papers for us wasnt sure.  But this fella spent some time in a foster home before being brought to the adoption center.  The poor thing lived in that tiny cage for almost 2 months before we came in and brought him home.  The volunteer told us that he had been there the longest of all the current residents, and he just keeps getting passed up.  I kind of took that as a sign.  He immediately stood out to me because of his colors, but when I first was able to pick him up and hold him.  I pretty much just melted and said, yep he is coming with us.

I think Sora has found his place to relax while I game and do random stuff on my computer. Of all the spots he tried, He stayed here the longest.

And he may or may not be named after a certain character...   *ponders*

This was Friday evening when I came home from work.  This was a favorite spot of my previous kitty. And I do believe Sora has taken to it.  Found him there this morning when I got up.  So it has officially been reclaimed.

PSA if you have a male cat

images.description:
This is my cat Rex rocking his collar of shame, a day after I rushed him to the vet when I woke up to find him peeing blood.

I didn’t realize this, but male cats can get a blockage in their urethra because it’s super narrow. My vet explained that cats can die in as little as 24 hours because if they can’t pee, they go into kidney failure:

https://www.aspca.org/news/pet-health-alert-urinary-blockage-cats-can-be-life-threatening

A lot of cats apparently don’t have noticeable symptoms until they’re blocked. With Rex, the night before when I came home from work, he didn’t rush to be fed like usual. When I went to bed, he didn’t curl up at my shoulder like he usually does. That was it, and I thought it was weird but not an emergency.

I was wrong, and it’s going to take a while for me not to feel guilty about that. I could have prevented him being in pain that night if I’d called my vet.

As it was, I nearly lost him. At the vet they took a urine sample and it was cherry red with all the blood in it, and his kidneys were already shutting down.

Luckily, my vet is a rockstar. Rex got the good stuff to knock him out, my vet put in a catheter, and he spent the next three days getting IV fluids to flush his system and help his kidneys recover.

This is Rex just after I brought him home, happy about getting his belly scritched just the way he likes.

If you have a male cat, and he starts acting weird at all, especially about not eating or using his litterbox, please call your vet to be safe!!
